fig.pixel_format = PIXFORMAT_JPEG; config.frame_size = camera_framesize; config.jpeg_quality = 12; config.fb_count = 1; // if more than one, i2s runs in continuous mode. Use only with JPEG // Init Camera esp_err_t err = esp_camera_init(&config); if (err != ESP_OK) { Serial.printf(\\"Camera init failed with error 0x%x\\", err); return; } // Initialize inputs and outputs pinMode(doorbellPin, INPUT_PULLUP); pinMode(hallSensorPin, INPUT_PULLUP); doorLockServo.attach(servoPin); // Define server routes server.on(\\"/\\", handleRoot); server.on(\\"/open-door\\", handleOpenDoor); server.on(\\"/capture\\", handleCapture); server.on(\\"/stream\\", handleStream); // Start server server.begin(); } void loop() { // Handle incoming server requests server.handleClient(); // Handle doorbell and hall sensor logic here // (You'll need to integrate this with the streaming endpoint) } \`\`\` # Additional Implementations: 1. Setup the proper camera frame size and quality for your network capabilities. 2. Implement a function to check the doorbell sensor state and begin streaming if activated. 3. Implement the \`/capture\` endpoint logic to take a photo and save it to an SD card (if attached and mounted). 4. Write logic in the \`loop()\` function to continuously check the hall sensor state and deactivate the system (stop streaming) accordingly. 5. You will need to implement the \`/stream\` endpoint logic for the MJPEG video stream. You'll also need to test and calibrate the servo motion, assign actual GPIO pins based on your ESP32-CAM module's pinout, and possibly prepare your web application with JavaScript to handle the AJAX requests for door opening and image capturing. Remember, security is important in IoT projectsâ€”especially one that provides physical access to your propertyâ€”so consider proper authentication mechanisms within your web application and secure the Wi-Fi communication."},{"prompt":"Based on the additional implementations for 1. you mentioned please generate complete code saperately so that i can implement in the above code later also tell me where in the code i need to implement code ? also for fram sise and quality and network capabilities , i want frame size like can be easyly seen on a mobile screen of camera ouput, for quality of video, as this is MJPEG i want sweet spot between quality and framerate, for network capabilities so i have 20 mbs connection of fiber optics !","completion":"To set the frame size and quality of your ESP32-CAM module for video streaming in a way that should be suitable for viewing on a mobile screen and have a good balance between quality and framerate, you can opt for a smaller framesize such as VGA (640x480), which should be clear enough on mobile devices while not demanding too much network bandwidth. For a fiber optics connection with a speed of 20 Mbps, bandwidth shouldn't be a major issue for MJPEG streaming at VGA resolution; however, keeping the quality setting around 10-15 should provide a reasonable balance. Here is the separate snippet for the camera configuration that you can incorporate into your code: \`\`\`cpp // Camera configuration settings void setupCamera() { camera_config_t camera_config = { .pin_pwdn = CAM_PIN_PWDN, .pin_reset = CAM_PIN_RESET, .pin_xclk = CAM_PIN_XCLK, .pin_sccb_sda = CAM_PIN_SIOD, .pin_sccb_scl = CAM_PIN_SIOC, .pin_d7 = CAM_PIN_D7, .pin_d6 = CAM_PIN_D6, .pin_d5 = CAM_PIN_D5, .pin_d4 = CAM_PIN_D4, .pin_d3 = CAM_PIN_D3, .pin_d2 = CAM_PIN_D2, .pin_d1 = CAM_PIN_D1, .pin_d0 = CAM_PIN_D0, .pin_vsync = CAM_PIN_VSYNC, .pin_href = CAM_PIN_HREF, .pin_pclk = CAM_PIN_PCLK, // XCLK 20MHz or 10MHz both are fine .xclk_freq_hz = 20000000, .ledc_timer = LEDC_TIMER_0, .ledc_channel = LEDC_CHANNEL_0, .pixel_format = PIXFORMAT_JPEG, //YUV422,GRAYSCALE,RGB565,JPEG .frame_size = FRAMESIZE_VGA, // FRAMESIZE_ + QVGA(320x240) / VGA(640x480) / SVGA / â€¦ / UXGA(1600x1200) .jpeg_quality = 12, // Quality of JPEG output. Lower means better quality, 0-63 .fb_count = 1, // Number of frame buffers to be allocated. More means more memory. }; // Camera init esp_err_t err = esp_camera_init(&camera_config); if (err != ESP_OK) { Serial.printf(\\"Camera init failed with error 0x%x\\", err); return; } } \`\`\` You would place the \`setupCamera()\` function before the \`setup()\` function in your code, and then you need to call it from within \`setup()\` like this: \`\`\`cpp void setup() { Serial.begin(115200); // Setup camera setupCamera(); ... // Continue with the rest of the setup ... } \`\`\` Before doing so, ensure the pin definitions in the configuration match your ESP32-CAM module's pinout. The comment at the \`frame_size\` line explains the various options available, and you can choose between them based on your needs. Furthermore, the \`jpeg_quality\` property is a little counterintuitive: a lower value means higher quality and a bigger image size. In your case, a \`jpeg_quality\` around 12 is set, which represents a medium quality image so as not to stress the network capabilities while maintaining a decent viewing experience. Adjust this setting as needed based on the actual performance you observe during testing. Finally, remember to integrate this code with the portions related to the HTML page serving, button handling, and servo/MJPEG streaming logic."},{"prompt":"i want you to please merge the respective camera confugration setting code you provide with the actual above code","completion":"Certainly! Below is the complete code that merges the camera configuration settings with the web server setup and other elements that were previously discussed. This integrated sketch sets up an ESP32-CAM server that allows for streaming MJPEG video and controlling a servo motor to open a door. It includes a basic web interface with buttons for opening the door and capturing images, as well as placeholders for the video streaming functionality. \`\`\`cpp #include <WiFi.h> #include <WebServer.h> #include <Servo.h> #include \\"esp_camera.h\\" // Replace with 